Hawaii Can Wait
---------------

In those bizarre days, Zero-G took off. Al Roker
took a flight and filmed a segment for the Today show. CBS News=E2=80=99s N=
orah O=E2=80=99Donnell did, too. =E2=80=9CAll of a sudden, it was becoming =
a thing,=E2=80=9D Gohd said. Business at Zero-G had improved so much that b=
y the end of 2022, Gohd was ready to turn things over to his chief operatin=
g officer and head back to Hawaii, where he lives now. =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=
=99s work on my exit package,=E2=80=9D he told his board, =E2=80=9Cconsider=
ing that basically I=E2=80=99ve taken this thing from zero to hero in three=
 years.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Alas, Hawaii would have to wait. No need to get into the gory details here,=
, but suffice it to say, six months later, the company was in worse shape t=
han Gohd had found it in 2019: no plane, no pilots, no money. Again, most o=
f the board quit, leaving just Gohd=E2=80=99s chosen successor as C.E.O. an=
d Gohd. He brought back Cronise as a board member and fired the C.E.O. He g=
ot the pilots to return and refocused on
training NASA astronauts and marketing the weightlessness experience to the=
 general public. In January 2024, he brought on Kevin Sproge, a test pilot =
and former head of commercial pilot training at Blue Origin, to be the new =
C.E.O. Gohd, now the company=E2=80=99s active executive chairman, hopes to =
soon return to just being a board member=E2=80=94and to Hawaii=E2=80=94and =
to let Sproge have full control.

=C2=A0

Despite
the company=E2=80=99s challenges, Gohd is aiming high. He told me that =E2=
=80=9Cmanufacturing in space=E2=80=9D could be a big opportunity for Zero-G=
, although I wasn=E2=80=99t exactly clear on how that would work. He thinks=
 there is interest in zero-gravity flights internationally and that in thre=
e years=E2=80=99 time, Zero-G could be a $30 million to $40 million EBIT bu=
siness. He=E2=80=99s shooting for around $20 million in revenues for 2025 a=
nd $6 million in profit, and is trying to raise around $15 million of new m=
oney at a $35 million
valuation. He=E2=80=99s hoping to buy a second plane, allowing for more com=
mercial flights and a proper maintenance schedule. =E2=80=9CHaving a second=
 airplane doesn=E2=80=99t double the valuation, it triples it,=E2=80=9D he =
said.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

He=E2=80=99s also hoping a ride on a Zero-G flight will become a rewards pr=
ogram of sorts for top performers in business and other disciplines, a way =
to create accentuated bonds of trust for participants who experience
weightlessness together. And he=E2=80=99s proven skilled at attracting medi=
a attention for the business, from The Mooch to Norah to, well, me, I suppo=
se. In 2007, Stephen Hawking, who had been bound to a wheelchair for 40 yea=
rs, experienced weightlessness on a Zero-G flight. Kate Upton, wearing a bi=
kini, got a solo ride on the plane for the Sports Illustrated Swimsuit Issu=
e in 2022. (Sorry, I did not receive a discount code for my exalted Dry Pow=
der readers.)
One thing is for sure: It=E2=80=99s a novel experience to watch control fre=
aks and masters of the universe find themselves in an environment they can=
