28.799999999999997px;"><strong>Gravity Falls</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table class=3D"c4" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspaci=
ng=3D"0" role=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspa=
ce:0pt;word-break:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-=
bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Zero-G was founded in 1993 by entrepreneur and =
longtime space
enthusiast <strong>Peter Diamandis</strong> and two friends=E2=80=94NASA as=
tronaut <strong>Byron Lichtenberg</strong> and engineer <strong>Ray Cronise=
</strong>. Eager to experience weightlessness like an astronaut, Diamandis =
raised a $10 million seed funding round from investors including <strong>El=
on Musk</strong>, <strong>Sergey Brin</strong>, and <strong>Esther Dyson</s=
trong>. It took the F.A.A. 11 years to certify Zero-G for taking civilians =
up on a flight. =E2=80=9CThey did not want that responsibility, of
basically certifying a plane that, when you think about it, goes up and nos=
edives,=E2=80=9D Gohd recalled.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom=
:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">As he contemplate=
d joining the company during its dark days, Gohd went into overdrive, learn=
ing everything he could about Zero-G and the bespoke zero-gravity flight in=
dustry. He spoke with creditors, vendors, customers, and the remaining empl=
oyees. They all seemed eager to keep Zero-G alive. =E2=80=9CI felt
that the cultural issues could be solved, the financial issues could be sol=
ved, the demand, I knew, was there,=E2=80=9D Gohd told me.=C2=A0</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bot=
tom:0px;">At the time, the company desperately needed a new equity infusion=
=2E Gohd made five calls and, miraculou=
sly, received five positive responses=
=E2=80=94this is a business with significant risks<em> and </em>CapEx requi=
rements, although they are not insurmountable. He even convinced his
new investors to wire the funds before the deal documents could be drafted,=
 using the money to pay the overdue insurance bill and cover maintenance on=
 the jet. Then, he started marketing.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom=
:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Gohd reached out to his friend <str=
ong>Anthony Scaramucci </strong>to see if The Mooch would be willing to pro=
mote Zero-G at his annual SALT Conference in Las Vegas. He contacted <stron=
g>Mike Milken</strong>=E2=80=99s people to see if he=E2=80=99d feature
Zero-G at the annual Milken Conference at the Beverly Hilton. He sent a pro=
posal to <strong>Rob Wiesenthal</strong>, the C.E.O. of Blade, to see if Ze=
ro-G could partner up with the chopper company. They all agreed to help out=
=2E He also got creative about raisi=
ng new equity with a =E2=80=9Cstandby rig=
hts offering,=E2=80=9D where an investor or investors agree to buy the shar=
es in a company if other investors don=E2=80=99t exercise their rights to b=
uy shares. </p></div>
