ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In those bizarre days, Zero-G took off. <strong=
>Al Roker</strong>
took a flight and filmed a segment for the <em>Today</em> show. CBS News=E2=
=80=99s <strong>Norah O=E2=80=99Donnell</strong> did, too. =E2=80=9CAll of =
a sudden, it was becoming a thing,=E2=80=9D Gohd said. Business at Zero-G h=
ad improved so much that by the end of 2022, Gohd was ready to turn things =
over to his chief operating officer and head back to Hawaii, where he lives=
 now. =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s work on my exit package,=E2=80=9D he told his =
board, =E2=80=9Cconsidering that basically I=E2=80=99ve taken this thing fr=
om zero to hero in three years.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;marg=
in-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Alas, Ha=
waii would have to wait. No need to get into the gory details here,, but su=
ffice it to say, six months later, the company was in worse shape than Gohd=
 had found it in 2019: no plane, no pilots, no money. Again, most of the bo=
ard quit, leaving just Gohd=E2=80=99s chosen successor as C.E.O. and Gohd. =
He brought back Cronise as a board member and fired the C.E.O. He got the p=
ilots to return and refocused on
training NASA astronauts and marketing the weightlessness experience to the=
 general public. In January 2024, he brought on <strong>Kevin Sproge</stron=
g>, a test pilot and former head of commercial pilot training at Blue Origi=
n, to be the new C.E.O. Gohd, now the company=E2=80=99s active executive ch=
airman, hopes to soon return to just being a board member=E2=80=94and to Ha=
waii=E2=80=94and to let Sproge have full control.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;m=
argin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Despi=
te
the company=E2=80=99s challenges, Gohd is aiming high. He told me that =E2=
=80=9Cmanufacturing in space=E2=80=9D could be a big opportunity for Zero-G=
, although I wasn=E2=80=99t exactly clear on how that would work. He thinks=
 there is interest in zero-gravity flights internationally and that in thre=
e years=E2=80=99 time, Zero-G could be a $30 million to $40 million EBIT bu=
siness. He=E2=80=99s shooting for around $20 million in revenues for 2025 a=
nd $6 million in profit, and is trying to raise around $15 million of new m=
oney at a $35 million
valuation. He=E2=80=99s hoping to buy a second plane, allowing for more com=
mercial flights and a proper maintenance schedule. =E2=80=9CHaving a second=
 airplane doesn=E2=80=99t double the valuation, it triples it,=E2=80=9D he =
said.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;">He=E2=80=99s also hoping a ride on a Zero-G flight will beco=
me a rewards program of sorts for top performers in business and other disc=
iplines, a way to create accentuated bonds of trust for participants who ex=
perience
weightlessness together. And he=E2=80=99s proven skilled at attracting medi=
a attention for the business, from The Mooch to Norah to, well, me, I suppo=
se. In 2007, <strong>Stephen Hawking</strong>, who had been bound to a whee=
lchair for 40 years, experienced weightlessness on a Zero-G flight. <strong=
>Kate Upton</strong>, wearing a bikini, got a solo ride on the plane for th=
e <em>Sports Illustrated</em> Swimsuit Issue in 2022. (Sorry, I did not rec=
eive a discount code for my exalted Dry Powder readers.)
One thing is for sure: It=E2=80=99s a novel experience to watch control fre=
aks and masters of the universe find themselves in an environment they can=
=E2=80=99t control while experiencing something they=E2=80=99ve never exper=
ienced before. Sounds like a nice holiday gift, doesn=E2=80=99t it?</p></di=
v>
